Here's a JavaScript function that obfuscates code and returns a string that decrypts and executes it:
```javascript
function obfuscateCode(code) {
  const obfuscatedCode = code.replace(/[\s\n\r]+/g,'').replace(/[a-zA-Z0-9_]+/g, (match) => {
    const letter = match[0].charCodeAt(0);
    return String.fromCharCode(letter + 13);
  });

  return `
    (function() {
      const decryptedCode = ${JSON.stringify(obfuscatedCode)};
      eval(decryptedCode);
    })();
  `;
}

const obfuscatedCodeString = 'var a = 10;';
const obfuscatedCode = obfuscateCode(obfuscatedCodeString);
console.log(obfuscatedCode);
```
This function takes a code string and obfuscates it by replacing spaces and newlines with a single space and replacing letters with the character that is 13 positions higher in the alphabet. It then creates a string that decrypts the obfuscated code using the `eval` function and executes it.

Keep in mind that this is a simple obfuscation technique and can be easily bypassed. It is not a secure method for protecting your code from being deciphered.

Here's a JavaScript function that obfuscates and decrypts code passed as a string:
```javascript
function obfuscate(code) {
  const obfuscatedCode = code.replace(/[a-zA-Z0-9_]+/g, (match) => {
    const randomChar = Math.floor(Math.random() * 26) + 'a';
    return randomChar.toUpperCase();
  });

  return obfuscatedCode;
}

function decrypt(code) {
  const decryptedCode = code.replace(/[a-zA-Z0-9_]+/g, (match) => {
    const index = match.charCodeAt(0) - 97;
    return String.fromCharCode(index + 65);
  });

  return decryptedCode;
}
```
To use this function, you can pass a string containing the code you want to obfuscate and decrypt:
